1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:05,862
Why does this give you such extraordinary representations in unsupervised fashion?

2
00:00:06,604 --> 00:00:15,261
And I sort of, I have two things that I think contribute mostly to this.

3
00:00:16,163 --> 00:00:19,930
So if we look at the question of why, right?

4
00:00:19,910 --> 00:00:24,357
The first thing I think is the augmentations.

5
00:00:25,318 --> 00:00:35,753
The augmentations have played a large role, not as much in NLP.

6
00:00:35,833 --> 00:00:37,716
In NLP, we do it a little bit differently.

7
00:00:37,696 --> 00:00:44,189
but augmentations in computer vision and self supervised learning have a central role.

8
00:00:44,570 --> 00:00:50,963
And it's really important that you have the correct ones, which is a thing they also say right here, right?

9
00:00:50,983 --> 00:00:57,696
They really stress that this multi crop augmentation is quite important.

10
00:00:57,676 --> 00:01:00,920
So augmentations seem to be central.

11
00:01:01,300 --> 00:01:10,171
And to me, augmentations are a bit like that's where you put the, that's where you put the human prior.

12
00:01:10,231 --> 00:01:15,837
That's where you tell the model what it should pay attention to and what it shouldn't pay attention to, right?

13
00:01:16,198 --> 00:01:24,347
Because all the things you destroy with an augmentation, like you make the color brighter, that's, you tell the model color doesn't matter, right?

14
00:01:24,407 --> 00:01:26,890
Or brightness variations don't matter.

15
00:01:26,870 --> 00:01:34,857
So by augmenting, you tell the model what it should and shouldn't or, you know, what it shouldn't pay attention to, essentially.

16
00:01:35,238 --> 00:01:41,904
So all the things that, you know, it's the same if you have an, if you have a data set of dogs and cats, right?

17
00:01:42,804 --> 00:01:47,709
And, um, you know, you tell it, you know, this is a dog, this is a dog, this is a dog.

18
00:01:47,969 --> 00:01:53,794
Essentially, you tell it, you shouldn't pay attention to, you know, what is different in these images.

19
00:01:53,834 --> 00:01:56,877
You should only pay attention to what is the same.

20
00:01:56,857 --> 00:02:01,223
And the augmentations, that's kind of where the knowledge goes in.

21
00:02:01,344 --> 00:02:17,447
So if we want to go towards fully, let's say fully autonomous self supervised learning, that's what we need to get rid of, we need to get rid of the augmentations, or we need to get rid of

22
00:02:17,427 --> 00:02:21,013
us designing augmentations for the domain.

23
00:02:21,134 --> 00:02:36,841
If we want this to be, you know, domain agnostic, and also if we want better image representations, because the probability that we as humans exactly capture the correct augmentations is zero, right?

24
00:02:36,982 --> 00:02:38,845
We seem to capture pretty good ones.

25
00:02:38,825 --> 00:02:44,592
But, you know, the probability that we have the best ones is like zero.

26
00:02:45,353 --> 00:02:45,453
Okay.

27
00:02:45,473 --> 00:02:52,102
The second thing, and this is a thing that's, I think more hidden is the data set.

28
00:02:52,702 --> 00:02:55,826
And what I mean is how the data set is constructed.

29
00:02:56,187 --> 00:03:01,093
So these things are often, you know, trained on something like ImageNet data set.

30
00:03:01,113 --> 00:03:02,875
And you can see

31
00:03:02,855 --> 00:03:10,234
in these pictures, there always seems to be like an object of interest in these in these pictures, right?

32
00:03:11,116 --> 00:03:19,277
Even if you train this from pictures in the wild, like you scrape pictures from Instagram or whatever,

33
00:03:19,257 --> 00:03:24,062
the way people don't take pictures of random things.

34
00:03:24,402 --> 00:03:33,391
People, if you're, you know, it would be pretty weird to have a picture and, you know, there's just like dirt road.

35
00:03:33,691 --> 00:03:37,795
Like it's just like dirt road and here's like, you know, a bit of grass.

36
00:03:38,476 --> 00:03:42,740
And you post this on social media and you're like, whoa, look at this.

37
00:03:44,021 --> 00:03:45,703
So,

38
00:03:45,683 --> 00:03:57,991
by how you construct the data set, even if you scrape it from the internet by how humanity takes pictures, you are implicitly telling the model what's important.

39
00:03:58,331 --> 00:04:00,857
So the model learns

40
00:04:00,837 --> 00:04:02,039
How should I say this?

41
00:04:02,800 --> 00:04:09,833
How you make the data set speaks a lot about where your attention goes.

42
00:04:10,674 --> 00:04:13,679
And that's what you feed the model, right?

43
00:04:14,401 --> 00:04:23,757
So these things, these self supervised methods in this way, they rely a lot on data set construction.

44
00:04:23,737 --> 00:04:32,688
So we shouldn't expect this to transfer to domains where we get like random IID data from the world, because these things aren't IID.

45
00:04:33,129 --> 00:04:38,315
We tell the model pretty clearly by the data we give it, what's important, what isn't.

46
00:04:39,557 --> 00:04:41,780
So that is a little bit of my opinion.

47
00:04:41,800 --> 00:04:43,182
And I think that's correct, right?

48
00:04:43,322 --> 00:04:51,432
I think the model, if we have self supervised learning, the information should be taken from the data set.

49
00:04:51,412 --> 00:04:51,854
Right.

50
00:04:51,874 --> 00:05:00,872
So that the model should look at the data sense a what seems to be given how this data set is, what seem to be the important things in there.

51
00:05:01,816 --> 00:05:05,050
I'm more a fan of getting rid of the augmentations.

